result.execSummary:
The defendant Dominic D. Ecklund - #548835 was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver Heroin (<3g) [Modifiers: Repeater], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(d)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Order Granting the Defendant's Motin for Postconviction Relief

2:35 p.m.  Court in session.  Case case.  
Student Intern Hahn appears for the State under the supervision of DA Necci.  
Defendant Dominic D. Ecklund appears by VIDEO from Racine Correctional, in custody with attorney John Richard Breffeilh.  
Matter is before the Court on the Defendant's Rule 809.30 motion for postconviction relief.  The State is conceding this issue.  Court grants the Defendant's request.  Attorney Breffeilh will submit an Order.  
Continued discussion between Court and Attorneys in response to question by Attorney Necci.  Attorney Necci argues the Court has the power to determine its discretion at this point.  Attorney Breffeilh agrees. Court did rely upon the Statute and did not believe it had any discretion at the time.  Argument by Ms. Hahn.  State is arguing for a single surcharge to be assessed.  Attorney Breffeilh indicates that Mr. Ecklund may have given a previous DNA sample and been assessed the surcharge.  Continued discussion between Court and Attorneys.  If he has paid the surcharge, the State is not asking that he pay it again.  DA Necci indicates that if he has provided a sample in the past, the State is not asking for a surcharge.  Attorney Breffeilh advises the Defendant has prior convictions and believes he has likely given a sample and been assessed the surcharge.  Clerk checks CCAP records.  The Defendant has been ordered to give a DNA sample and has previously paid the DNA surcharge on another case.  Defendant's Motion is GRANTED and the DNA surcharge on this case will be vacated.  Attorney Breffeilh will submit an Order.
